                title: "The government wants to start sending millions of Americans a check",
                content: '<h1>The government wants to start sending millions of Americans a check. Here&rsquo;s how to use it wisely</h1><div><p>Some good news &ndash; in the form of money &ndash; may be coming to Americans soon.</p><p>On Tuesday, Treasury Secretary Steve Mnuchin said that the Trump administration plans to move &ldquo;immediately&rdquo; to send money to Americans as the coronavirus cripples the economy.</p><div><p>&ldquo;Americans need cash now,&rdquo; Mnuchin said, indicating checks could come in the next two weeks.</p><p>The announcement follows much discussion over how the government could act to help shore up American workers&rsquo; bank balances now, with so many businesses temporarily closed or operating at reduced capacities.</p></div><h2 class="ArticleBody-subtitle">A thousand dollars for everyone</h2><div class="group"><p>Sen. Mitt Romney, R-Utah, said this week that he wants the government to send every adult $1,000.</p><p>Details on how big the checks the Trump administration hopes to deploy have not been disclosed. Of course, any plans would need a green light from Congress.</p><p>&ldquo;The basic idea of getting money into the economy very quickly is a good idea,&rdquo; said Leonard Burman, institute fellow at the Urban Institute, a non-partisan think tank, and co-founder of the Tax Policy Center.&nbsp;</p><div id="MidResponsive-3" class="" data-module="mps-slot"></div><p>It is also an improvement over potential payroll tax cuts, another idea that has been touted by the Trump administration and others in recent weeks.</p></div>',
